nd Fishkin\nBest for: Contrarian, data-backed takes on search marketing trends\n\nKevin Indig. Growth Advisor, Author of Growth Memo \u00b7 70,000+ followers\nAmong the rare voices who can connect SEO directly to product growth, Kevin Indig stands above the rest. He advises companies like Shopify, Reddit, and Notion on SEO and growth. His weekly newsletter, Growth Memo, dissects search trends, AI disruption, and organic growth strategy.\n\nWebsite: kevinIndig.com\nX/Twitter: @Kevin_Indig\nNewsletter: Growth Memo\nLinkedIn: Kevin Indig\nBest for: SEO strategy for product-led and SaaS companies\n\nBrian Dean. Founder, Backlinko (Semrush) \u00b7 100,000+ followers\nFew individuals have contributed more original frameworks to SEO than Brian Dean, creator of the Skyscraper Technique. He built Backlinko into one of the most-cited SEO resources online before Semrush acquired it. Brian now focuses on data-driven content about link building, content optimization, and search traffic growth.\n\nWebsite: backlinko.com\nX/Twitter: @BrianEDean\nYouTube: Brian Dean (500K+ subscribers)\nLinkedIn: Brian Dean\nBest for: Data-driven link building and content optimization frameworks\n\nCyrus Shepard. Founder, Zyppy SEO \u00b7 40,000+ followers\nWhen it comes to original CTR research and title tag science, no one on LinkedIn publishes more rigorous data than Cyrus Shepard. He founded Zyppy, an SEO software company focused on title tag testing and CTR optimization, and previously led the content team at Moz. His LinkedIn posts feature original research, CTR experiments, and on-page optimization data.\n\nWebsite: zyppy.com\nX/Twitter: @CyrusShepard\nNewsletter: Zyppy SEO Newsletter\nLinkedIn: Cyrus Shepard\nBest for: Original CTR research and title tag optimization data\n\nTim Soulo. CMO, Ahrefs \u00b7 45,000+ followers\nAs the marketing mind behind Ahrefs, Tim Soulo has shaped how an entire generation of SEOs think about data. He shares deep dives into search data, content strategy, and SEO metrics, regularly publishing original studies that challenge common SEO assumptions with evidence.\n\nWebsite: ahrefs.com/blog\nX/Twitter: @timsoulo\nYouTube: Ahrefs\nLinkedIn: Tim Soulo\nBest for: Data-driven SEO insights backed by Ahrefs research\n\nGlen Allsopp. Founder, Detailed.com \u00b7 20,000+ followers\nGlen Allsopp has built a reputation as the SEO industry's most incisive investigative analyst. He runs Detailed.com, a site that exposes who owns the top-ranking pages in Google, and publishes original research on search monopolies, affiliate SEO, and content strategy that reveals patterns most SEO professionals never notice.\n\nWebsite: detailed.com\nX/Twitter: @ViperChill\nNewsletter: Detailed Newsletter\nLinkedIn: Glen Allsopp\nBest for: Deep investigative analysis of who actually dominates Google search results\n\nDharmesh Shah. CTO and Co-Founder, HubSpot \u00b7 700,000+ followers\nAs the technical co-founder of HubSpot, Dharmesh Shah helped define what modern inbound marketing looks like at scale. His LinkedIn posts cover content strategy, AI in marketing, and organic growth, bringing a rare technical founder perspective to SEO and content marketing.\n\nWebsite: hubspot.com\nX/Twitter: @dharmesh\nLinkedIn: Dharmesh Shah\nBest for: Inbound marketing strategy and content-led growth at enterprise scale\n\n\nBuild your SEO content system on autopilot. Stacc publishes 30 blog posts per month, optimized for search, so you can focus on strategy.\nStart for $1 \u2192\n\n\nThese are the voices that have shaped how the SEO industry thinks about crawlability, indexation, structured data, site architecture, and the engineering side of search. Each one has earned their place through original research and tested expertise.\nMike King. Founder, iPullRank \u00b7 30,000+ followers\nNo one on LinkedIn explains the engineering behind Google rankings with more depth or clarity than Mike King. He founded iPullRank, an agency known for enterprise technical SEO, and digs into patents, information retrieval systems, and how Google works under the hood in a way that most influencers never attempt.\n\nWebsite: ipullrank.com\nX/Twitter: @iPullRank\nYouTube: iPullRank\nLinkedIn: Mike King\nBest for: Deep technical SEO and Google patent analysis\n\nAleyda Solis. International SEO Consultant, Founder of Orainti \u00b7 109,000+ followers\nAmong technical and international SEO consultants worldwide, Aleyda Solis has earned recognition as one of the most respected practitioners in the field. She runs the SEO Fomo newsletter and posts daily about algorithm updates, search intent, crawlability, and global SEO strategy.\n\nWebsite: aleydasolis.com\nX/Twitter: @aleyda\nYouTube: Aleyda Solis\nNewsletter: SEO Fomo\nLinkedIn: Aleyda Solis\nBest for: International SEO, real-time news curation, and practical frameworks\n\nCrystal Carter. Head of SEO Communications, Wix \u00b7 25,000+ followers\nCrystal Carter has become one of the clearest voices on structured data and SERP features in the industry. She leads SEO communications at Wix, speaks at major search conferences, and translates Google documentation into actionable advice about schema markup and how search engines parse content.\n\nWebsite: wix.com/seo\nX/Twitter: @CrystalontheWeb\nLinkedIn: Crystal Carter\nBest for: Structured data, SERP features, and AI Overviews optimization\n\nJohn Mueller. Search Advocate, Google \u00b7 55,000+ followers\nAs Google's most accessible public voice on search-related questions, John Mueller has helped millions of SEOs understand how indexing and crawlability actually work. His LinkedIn content clarifies misconceptions about how Google treats websites, covering Core Web Vitals and Google Search Console directly from the source.\n\nWebsite: developers.google.com/search\nX/Twitter: @JohnMu\nLinkedIn: John Mueller\nBest for: Official Google guidance on technical SEO and search quality\n\nDanny Sullivan. Public Liaison for Search, Google \u00b7 50,000+ followers\nDanny Sullivan founded Search Engine Watch and Search Engine Land before becoming Google's public liaison for search. A career trajectory that makes him one of the most authoritative voices on ranking systems that exists. His posts explain how Google evaluates content quality directly from the inside.\n\nWebsite: developers.google.com/search\nX/Twitter: @dannysullivan\nLinkedIn: Danny Sullivan\nBest for: Official Google ranking system explanations and update context\n\nCindy Krum. Founder and CEO, MobileMoxie \u00b7 12,000+ followers\nCindy Krum coined the term \"fraggles\" for fragment-based indexing. A contribution that alone marks her as a distinctive voice in mobile SEO. She specializes in mobile-first indexing, app SEO, and how Google processes content on mobile devices.\n\nWebsite: mobilemoxie.com\nX/Twitter: @Suzzicks\nLinkedIn: Cindy Krum\nBest for: Mobile SEO, entity-based indexing, and mobile-first strategy\n\nJR Oakes. VP of Product, Locomotive Agency \u00b7 15,000+ followers\nJR Oakes represents a rare combination: the data scientist and the technical SEO practitioner in one. He builds tools, runs experiments, and shares code-based approaches to search problems including Python for SEO, log file analysis, and large-scale crawl optimization.\n\nWebsite: locomotive.agency\nX/Twitter: @jroakes\nLinkedIn: JR Oakes\nBest for: Data science applications in technical SEO and Python automation\n\nBritney Muller. Data Scientist, Freelance SEO \u00b7 20,000+ followers\nBritney Muller has done more than almost anyone to bring data science thinking into mainstream SEO practice. She previously led SEO research at Moz and continues to publish on machine learning for SEO, data visualization, and technical audits that make complex data concepts accessible.\n\nWebsite: britneymuller.com\nX/Twitter: @BritneyMuller\nLinkedIn: Britney Muller\nBest for: Machine learning, data science, and analytical approaches to SEO\n\nJesse McDonald. Director of Technical SEO, IBM \u00b7 10,000+ followers\nManaging SEO for one of the largest enterprise websites on the internet qualifies Jesse McDonald as one of the most battle-tested technical practitioners on this list. He posts about enterprise crawl management, site architecture, and JavaScript SEO from direct, massive-scale experience.\n\nWebsite: jessemcdonald.net\nX/Twitter: @JesseSeoGeek\nLinkedIn: Jesse McDonald\nBest for: Enterprise-scale technical SEO and JavaScript rendering\n\n\nTechnical SEO and content, handled for you. We optimize every post for E-E-A-T, internal linking, and search intent. No SEO team required.\nStart for $1 \u2192\n\n\nThese influencers have earned recognition as the voices that bridge the gap between SEO and content strategy. The practitioners who proved that writing, distribution, and brand building are inseparable from organic growth.\nAnn Handley. Chief Content Officer, MarketingProfs \u00b7 450,000+ followers\nAnn Handley wrote \"Everybody Writes,\" one of the most influential content marketing books in existence, and her status as a LinkedIn voice reflects decades of genuine craft leadership. She posts about writing quality, content strategy, email marketing, and brand storytelling. The creative foundation that makes SEO content writing actually work.\n\nWebsite: annhandley.com\nX/Twitter: @annhandley\nNewsletter: Total Annarchy\nLinkedIn: Ann Handley\nBest for: Content writing craft and brand storytelling\n\nRoss Simmonds. Founder, Foundation Marketing \u00b7 80,000+ followers\nRoss Simmonds has become the loudest and most persuasive voice on LinkedIn for content distribution strategy. His central argument. That most content fails not because it is bad, but because nobody distributes it. Has reshaped how B2B SaaS brands think about organic content.\n\nWebsite: foundationinc.co\nX/Twitter: @TheCoolestCool\nYouTube: Ross Simmonds\nLinkedIn: Ross Simmonds\nBest for: Content distribution strategy and B2B content marketing\n\nDave Gerhardt. Founder, Exit Five \u00b7 100,000+ followers\nDave Gerhardt built Exit Five into the defining community for B2B marketers, and his LinkedIn presence reflects the same no-nonsense approach to connecting content strategy to business outcomes. He posts about brand building, content marketing strategy, positioning, and go-to-market, not just traffic numbers.\n\nWebsite: exitfive.com\nX/Twitter: @davegerhardt\nNewsletter: Exit Five Newsletter\nLinkedIn: Dave Gerhardt\nBest for: B2B marketing strategy and content-to-pipeline thinking\n\nAmanda Natividad. VP Marketing, SparkToro \u00b7 50,000+ followers\nAmanda Natividad coined the term \"zero-click content\". A concept that has become foundational to how marketers think about generative engine optimization and organic distribution in the AI search era. She writes about creating content that delivers value without requiring a click, and about audience research that goes beyond keyword volume.\n\nWebsite: sparktoro.com\nX/Twitter: @amandanat\nNewsletter: The Menu\nLinkedIn: Amanda Natividad\nBest for: Zero-click content strategy and audience research\n\nAndy Crestodina. Co-Founder, Orbit Media \u00b7 30,000+ followers\nAndy Crestodina publishes the annual Blogging Survey and has built one of the most data-backed bodies of content marketing work on the internet. His posts about content marketing strategy, analytics, and conversion optimization consistently set the standard for evidence-driven thinking in the field.\n\nWebsite: orbitmedia.com\nX/Twitter: @crestodina\nYouTube: Orbit Media Studios\nLinkedIn: Andy Crestodina\nBest for: Content strategy backed by original survey data and analytics\n\nJoe Pulizzi. Founder, Content Marketing Institute \u00b7 40,000+ followers\nJoe Pulizzi coined the term \"content marketing\" and founded Content Marketing Institute. Which means the entire industry is, in a real sense, built on his foundational thinking. His posts about content strategy, audience building, and media company thinking continue to influence how brands treat content as a business asset.\n\nWebsite: joepulizzi.com\nX/Twitter: @JoePulizzi\nNewsletter: The Tilt\nLinkedIn: Joe Pulizzi\nBest for: Content-first business strategy and audience monetization\n\nJay Baer. Author, Keynote Speaker \u00b7 60,000+ followers\nJay Baer wrote \"Youtility\" and has spent his career teaching brands to create content so genuinely useful that people would pay for it. A philosophy that aligns perfectly with what Google rewards in 2026. His LinkedIn posts cover customer experience, word-of-mouth marketing, and the content strategy underneath both.\n\nWebsite: jaybaer.com\nX/Twitter: @jaybaer\nYouTube: Jay Baer\nLinkedIn: Jay Baer\nBest for: Helpful content philosophy and customer-centric marketing\n\nLee Odden. CEO, TopRank Marketing \u00b7 25,000+ followers\nOver more than 20 years serving enterprise clients, Lee Odden has built one of the most consistent records in B2B content marketing and influencer-integrated SEO. He posts about content strategy, SEO integration, and how B2B brands build organic visibility in a way that reflects genuine long-term practice.\n\nWebsite: toprankmarketing.com\nX/Twitter: @leeodden\nLinkedIn: Lee Odden\nBest for: B2B content marketing and influencer-integrated SEO strategy\n\nJulia McCoy. President, Content at Scale \u00b7 35,000+ followers\nJulia McCoy built a content agency from scratch, sold it, and came back to lead Content at Scale. A trajectory that gives her rare credibility on the reality of scaling SEO blog writing at volume. Her posts about AI content workflows and content operations are among the most practically useful on LinkedIn.\n\nWebsite: contentascale.ai\nX/Twitter: @JuliaEMcCoy\nYouTube: Julia McCoy\nLinkedIn: Julia McCoy\nBest for: Scaling content production and AI-assisted writing workflows\n\nAlex Cattoni. Founder, Copy Posse \u00b7 30,000+ followers\nAlex Cattoni has built an 800K+ subscriber YouTube channel teaching copywriting. And her LinkedIn presence reflects the same talent for making persuasive writing frameworks accessible and immediately actionable. Her content helps SEO writers convert visitors into customers, not just attract traffic.\n\nWebsite: copyposse.com\nX/Twitter: @copyposse\nYouTube: Alex Cattoni (800K+ subscribers)\nLinkedIn: Alex Cattoni\nBest for: Conversion copywriting and persuasive content frameworks\n\n\nConsistent content is the foundation of SEO. We publish 30 to 80 optimized articles per month for businesses in 70+ industries.\nStart for $1 \u2192\n\n\nThese influencers have earned recognition as the definitive voices on Google Business Profile optimization, local pack rankings, citations, and review management. If you operate a local business or serve clients who do, these are your people.\nJoy Hawkins. Owner, Sterling Sky \u00b7 15,000+ followers\nJoy Hawkins is widely regarded as the top authority on Google Maps rankings and local pack behavior in the SEO industry. She runs Sterling Sky, a local SEO agency, moderates the Google Business Profile community, and runs controlled experiments on local search that no one else is replicating.\n\nWebsite: sterlingsky.ca\nX/Twitter: @JoyanneHawkins\nLinkedIn: Joy Hawkins\nBest for: Google Business Profile optimization and local pack ranking experiments\n\nDarren Shaw. Founder, Whitespark \u00b7 12,000+ followers\nDarren Shaw runs the annual Local Search Ranking Factors survey. The most cited research on local SEO ranking signals in existence. He founded Whitespark, a local SEO tool and citation management company, and his data shapes how the entire local SEO industry makes decisions.\n\nWebsite: whitespark.ca\nX/Twitter: @DarrenShaw_\nNewsletter: Whitespark Local SEO Newsletter\nLinkedIn: Darren Shaw\nBest for: Local search ranking factors research and citation management\n\nGreg Gifford. VP of Search, SearchLab Digital \u00b7 10,000+ followers\nGreg Gifford has earned a reputation as one of the most entertaining and genuinely useful local SEO speakers in the industry. He posts about local search strategy, GBP features, and multi-location SEO with conference-quality depth and a delivery style that makes technical content memorable.\n\nWebsite: searchlabdigital.com\nX/Twitter: @GregGifford\nLinkedIn: Greg Gifford\nBest for: Multi-location local SEO strategy and GBP optimization\n\nBen Fisher. Co-Founder, Steady Demand \u00b7 8,000+ followers\nAs a Google Business Profile Gold Product Expert, Ben Fisher has earned a level of platform recognition that sets him apart from most local SEO practitioners. He posts about GBP suspensions, review management, and local listing optimization. Troubleshooting the problems that stump everyone else.\n\nWebsite: steadydemand.com\nX/Twitter: @TheSocialDude\nLinkedIn: Ben Fisher\nBest for: Google Business Profile troubleshooting and suspension recovery\n\n\nThese influencers have earned recognition as the practitioners who moved the craft of link acquisition from dark arts to legitimate, repeatable strategy. Their work defines what modern link building actually looks like.\nPaddy Moogan. Co-Founder, Aira \u00b7 10,000+ followers\nPaddy Moogan wrote \"The Link Building Book\". The most complete published guide on the subject. Before co-founding Aira, a digital PR and SEO agency. His posts about link building strategies, digital PR campaigns, and outreach tactics reflect the perspective of someone who has shaped the discipline.\n\nWebsite: aira.net\nX/Twitter: @paddymoogan\nLinkedIn: Paddy Moogan\nBest for: Digital PR link building and outreach strategy\n\nRobbie Richards. VP of Marketing, Virayo \u00b7 15,000+ followers\nRobbie Richards has built a following by publishing some of the most detailed and immediately actionable link building case studies on the internet. His posts about outreach templates, guest posting strategies, and building authority through backlinks deliver step-by-step frameworks that practitioners can use today.\n\nWebsite: robbierichards.com\nX/Twitter: @RobbieRichMktg\