X/Twitter: @navahopkins\nLinkedIn: Navah Hopkins\nBest for: Integrated paid and organic search strategy\n\nPeep Laja. Founder, Wynter and CXL \u00b7 30,000+ followers\nPeep Laja built CXL into one of the most respected marketing education platforms and then founded Wynter to solve B2B messaging research. A sequence that makes him uniquely authoritative on the conversion side of SEO. His insights on messaging and positioning help SEOs write content that actually converts the traffic they earn.\n\nWebsite: peeplaja.com\nX/Twitter: @peeplaja\nLinkedIn: Peep Laja\nBest for: B2B messaging strategy, positioning, and conversion optimization\n\nBen Goodey. Content Researcher, How They Grow \u00b7 10,000+ followers\nBen Goodey writes the How They Grow newsletter dissecting how companies grow through content and SEO with original, deeply researched analysis. His posts break down the content strategies of successful companies in a way that turns competitive intelligence into actionable frameworks.\n\nWebsite: howtheygrow.co\nX/Twitter: @bengoodey\nLinkedIn: Ben Goodey\nBest for: Content growth strategy teardowns and company analysis\n\nStacey MacNaught. SEO and Digital PR Consultant \u00b7 8,000+ followers\nStacey MacNaught has earned recognition as one of the most results-oriented digital PR practitioners posting on LinkedIn. Her campaign results, outreach strategies, and lessons from large-scale digital PR work are shared with an honesty about what works and what does not that is genuinely useful.\n\nWebsite: staceymacnaught.co.uk\nX/Twitter: @StaceyMacNaught\nLinkedIn: Stacey MacNaught\nBest for: Digital PR campaigns, link building strategy, and outreach tactics\n\nRyan Law. VP of Content, Animalz \u00b7 10,000+ followers\nRyan Law leads content strategy at Animalz and has become one of the most trusted voices on content operations and editorial management for SaaS companies. His posts on SEO-driven content planning reflect years of running programs for some of the most demanding B2B software brands.\n\nWebsite: animalz.co\nX/Twitter: @ryantlaw\nLinkedIn: Ryan Law\nBest for: SaaS content operations and editorial management\n\nSam Dunning. Host, Breaking B2B Podcast \u00b7 12,000+ followers\nSam Dunning has built the Breaking B2B Podcast into a go-to resource for B2B companies trying to generate leads through organic search. His LinkedIn posts and podcast episodes focus with unusual precision on the connection between SEO and actual pipeline. Not just traffic.\n\nWebsite: breakingb2b.com\nX/Twitter: @SamDunning_\nLinkedIn: Sam Dunning\nBest for: B2B SEO, lead generation, and website optimization strategy\n\nMatthew Howells-Barby. VP of Growth, HubSpot \u00b7 15,000+ followers\nMatthew Howells-Barby scaled SEO at HubSpot. One of the largest and most competitive content operations in the world. Before co-founding Traffic Think Tank. His LinkedIn posts on growth strategy, SEO team building, and enterprise organic search come from a vantage point that very few practitioners have ever occupied.\n\nWebsite: matthewbarby.com\nX/Twitter: @MatthewBarby\nLinkedIn: Matthew Howells-Barby\nBest for: SEO at enterprise scale and building in-house SEO teams\n\nKaleigh Moore. Freelance Writer, SaaS and eCommerce \u00b7 10,000+ followers\nKaleigh Moore has built a freelance writing career at the top of the SaaS and eCommerce content market and her LinkedIn posts on content quality, editorial standards, and how to create content that ranks are shaped by that high-performance client experience.\n\nWebsite: kaleighmoore.com\nX/Twitter: @kaleighf\nLinkedIn: Kaleigh Moore\nBest for: SaaS content writing, freelance strategy, and editorial quality\n\nJake Ward. CEO, Byword.ai \u00b7 8,000+ followers\nJake Ward built Byword.ai and has become one of the clearest voices on how AI content and programmatic SEO can be deployed responsibly at scale. His posts offer a platform builder's perspective on AI content strategy that is grounded in real product experience rather than speculation.\n\nWebsite: byword.ai\nX/Twitter: @jakezward\nLinkedIn: Jake Ward\nBest for: AI content strategy, programmatic SEO, and content at scale\n\nConnor Lahey. SEO Lead, Semrush \u00b7 8,000+ followers\nConnor Lahey shares practical SEO insights from inside one of the largest SEO tool companies in the world, giving his posts on keyword strategy, content optimization, and search trends a data foundation that most individual practitioners cannot match.\n\nWebsite: semrush.com\nX/Twitter: @connorldigital\nBest for: Data-driven keyword strategy and content optimization insights\n\nJoel Klettke. Founder, Case Study Buddy \u00b7 10,000+ followers\nJoel Klettke has carved out a unique and genuinely valuable niche: B2B case studies that both rank in search and convert in sales cycles. His LinkedIn posts on case study creation and conversion copywriting show how SEO content and sales enablement content can serve the same piece of writing.\n\nWebsite: casestudybuddy.com\nX/Twitter: @JoelKlettke\nLinkedIn: Joel Klettke\nBest for: B2B case study creation, conversion copywriting, and SEO content that sells\n\n\nFollowing 100 people is a start. Building a useful learning feed requires intention. Here is a practical framework.\nStep 1: Follow all 80 from this list. Use the table of contents above to jump to each category. Follow and ring the bell for notifications on your top 10. LinkedIn limits bell notifications, so pick the voices most relevant to your current work.\nStep 2: Engage within the first week. Comment on at least 5 posts with specific thoughts, not generic praise. LinkedIn's algorithm surfaces more content from accounts you interact with. Active engagement unlocks better content in your timeline.\nStep 3: Save posts that contain frameworks. Use LinkedIn's bookmark feature. Create a collection for SEO insights you want to reference later when writing blog posts or building strategy documents. Bookmarked posts become your personal SEO reference library over time.\nStep 4: Join the conversation threads. The best SEO insights on LinkedIn often appear in the comments. Lily Ray's update threads attract analysis from dozens of practitioners. Kevin Indig's posts spark debates between agency owners and in-house SEOs. Reading the comments doubles the value of every post.\nStep 5: Audit your feed monthly. Unfollow accounts that post motivational fluff without substance. Add new voices you discover through the comments. Your feed should evolve as your SEO knowledge grows.\nStep 6: Apply 1 insight per week. The best feed means nothing without execution. Pick 1 tip from your feed each week and implement it on your site. That compounds faster than reading alone.\nStep 7: Cross-reference with other platforms. Many experts on this list also publish newsletters, YouTube channels, and podcast episodes. Aleyda runs SEO Fomo. Kevin runs Growth Memo. Subscribe to 2 or 3 newsletters from your favorite voices."
